				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{BLSO}}_{(0001){\mathrm{Al}}_{2}{\mathrm{O}}_{3}}^{{\mathrm{BaZrO}}_{3}/\mathrm{MgO}}$$\end{document} in the X-band frequency range, i.e., 8.5–12.5 GHz, overlapped with radiowave (104–1010 Hz) and microwave (109–1012 Hz) ranges. The high SE of ~ 13.2 dB at 10 GHz was comparable to those of metal films, metal meshes, and two-dimensional materials (see Additional file 1: Table S2 for a comparison of resistivity, SE, and infrared transmittance among potential electromagnetic shielding materials) [34–41]. The SE (= SEA + SER) can be divided into SEA and SER, which denote shielding by absorption through BLSO(0001)Al2O3BaZrO3/MgO\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
